tury BC, and where women were as welcome as men. Sellars then moves on to ancient Rome, where Epicurean influence flourished thanks to the poet Lucretius and his cohort. Throughout the book, Sellars draws on the ideas of Epicurus to offer a constructive way of thinking about the pleasures of friendship and our place in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEpicureans (Greek philosophy) 0aEpicureans (Greek philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aepicurus, short, guide, introduction, greek, philosophy, hellenistic, ancient, stoic, classic, reader, art, happiness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391900 cprintz978022679864640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226798783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226798783/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles